{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:48:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:48:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18266"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74128"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10980"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59619"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7417"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25538"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral canal is bounded by the inguinal ligament anteriorly and the lacunar ligament medially. Posteriorly the canal is bordered by pectineal ligament, superior ramus of the pubic bone and the pectineus muscle. The lateral component is a vein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this vein?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["External iliac","Femoral","Great saphenous","Small saphenous","Popliteal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral canal is a component of the femoral sheath, which is located within the femoral triangle. The femoral sheath contains the femoral artery, femoral vein, and the femoral canal, but not the femoral nerve. The femoral canal is situated medial to the \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral vein\u003C/strong\u003E and allows for its expansion during increased venous return, such as during exercise or increased intra-abdominal pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal iliac vein\u003C/strong\u003E is located superior to the femoral triangle and is not directly associated with the femoral canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreat saphenous vein\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial vein that drains into the femoral vein but is not contained within the femoral sheath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall saphenous vein\u003C/strong\u003E is another superficial vein that drains into the popliteal vein, not the femoral vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epopliteal vein\u003C/strong\u003E is located posteriorly in the knee region and is not related to the femoral canal or sheath.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The femoral canal allows for the expansion of the femoral vein during increased venous return.","The femoral sheath contains the femoral artery, vein, and canal, but not the nerve.","Understanding the anatomy of the femoral triangle is crucial for procedures like catheterisation."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59619"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18266"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59619"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T19:25:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T19:26:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10980"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74128"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m